  {
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>A Si and a Ge diode has identical physical dimensions. The band gap in Si is larger than that in Ge. An identical reverse bias is applied across the diodes</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "The reverse current in Ge is larger than that in Si"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "The reverse current in Si is larger than that in Ge"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "The reverse current is identical in the two diodes"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "The relative magnitude of the reverse currents cannot be determined from the given data only"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<ul>\n<li><p>The reverse saturation current in a diode mainly depends on the number of thermally generated electron-hole pairs.</p></li>\n<li><p>The number of thermally generated carriers depends <strong>exponentially</strong> on the band gap ($E_g$) of the semiconductor.</p></li>\n<li><p>The expression for reverse saturation current $I_s$ is:</p>\n<p>$$   I_s \\propto \\exp\\left(-\\frac{E_g}{2kT}\\right)   $$</p>\n<p>where $E_g$ is the band gap, $k$ is Boltzmann constant, and $T$ is absolute temperature.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Silicon (Si)</strong> has a <strong>larger band gap</strong> than <strong>Germanium (Ge)</strong>.</p></li>\n<li><p>Therefore,</p>\n<p>$$   E_{g,\\text{Si}} > E_{g,\\text{Ge}} \\implies I_{s,\\text{Si}} < I_{s,\\text{Ge}}   $$</p></li>\n<li><p>Thus, with an identical reverse bias:</p></li>\n<li><p>The reverse current in Ge is <strong>larger</strong> than that in Si.</p></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Option A:</strong> The reverse current in Ge is larger than that in Si</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2008,
    "yearKey": "wb-jee-2008",
    "difficulty": null
  },
